 opponents as irrelevant. Structured around an anti-war perspective, The Lamb and the Tiger critically examines the ageless genetic and more recent cultural (civilizational) explanations of war, concluding with a close look at the impact of war and right-wing politics on women and Indigenous peoples. The Lamb and the Tiger encourages Canadians to think about what kind of military and what kind of country they really want.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aAboriginals.  aAfghanistan.  aBalkans.  aCold War.  aIraq.  aPeace.  aRwanda.  aSomalia.  adividend.  afailed states.  agenetic and cultural basis of war.  aidentity politics.  akeeping.  aterrorism.  awar as public relations.  awar.  awarfare.  awarriors.  awomen and war.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060679940uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148751788540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487517885423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487517885.jpg  a978-3-11-060679-9  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-073776-9  DTL Humanities 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles